        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Compliance Forms Overview",
            Slug = "compliance-forms-overview",
            Summary = "What compliance forms are, which forms QB Engineer supports (W-4, I-9, state withholding, direct deposit, workers' comp, handbook), when forms need updating, and how they connect to payroll and onboarding.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/account/tax-forms"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","tax-forms","w-4","i-9","onboarding"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Compliance Forms Overview\n\nCompliance forms are the tax, work-eligibility, and policy sign-off documents that every employee has to complete. They're required by the government and by your company, and they feed directly into payroll, work verification, and staying compliant.\n\n### What Forms Are There?\n\nThere are six kinds of compliance forms:\n\n- **W-4 (Employee's Withholding Certificate)** — The IRS form that sets how much federal income tax comes out of your paycheck. You choose your filing status, note whether you have more than one job, claim dependents, and add any extra withholding.\n\n- **I-9 (Employment Eligibility Verification)** — The form that confirms who you are and that you're allowed to work in the U.S. It has two parts: your part (your citizenship status, personal info, and signature) and your employer's part (checking your documents within three business days of your start date). You provide ID documents from List A, or from List B plus List C.\n\n- **State Withholding** — Your state's income tax form. The system picks the right one for you based on your work location. Some states (like Texas, Florida, and Nevada) have no income tax and need no form. Some use the federal W-4 instead. States with their own form fill it out on screen.\n\n- **Direct Deposit** — Your bank details for getting paid electronically: bank name, account type, routing number, and account number. Sensitive numbers are hidden after you submit, showing only the last four digits.\n\n- **Workers' Compensation Acknowledgment** — Your sign-off that you understand the workplace-injury reporting rules.\n\n- **Employee Handbook Acknowledgment** — Your confirmation that you've received, read, and agree to follow the company handbook.\n\n### Getting Set Up\n\nAll six forms are built into the guided onboarding steps. As a new employee, you complete everything in one flow instead of hunting down each form on its own. Your Tax Forms page shows a banner linking to onboarding whenever you still have forms to finish.\n\nOnce onboarding is done, you can return to your Tax Forms page any time to review what you submitted, download signed copies, or update a form when your situation changes.\n\n### When Forms Need Updating\n\n- **W-4**: Any time your situation changes — marriage, divorce, new dependents, a second job, or a big change in income. There's no yearly requirement, but a yearly review is a good habit.\n- **I-9**: Can't be changed once submitted. Contact HR for corrections. It has to be re-checked when your work authorization documents expire.\n- **State Withholding**: When your situation changes, or when you move to a different state (your work location decides which state form applies).\n- **Direct Deposit**: Contact payroll to change your bank details.\n- **Workers' Comp / Handbook**: Usually signed once during onboarding. You may be asked to sign again if the policies change.\n\n### How Forms Connect to Payroll\n\nWhat you enter on these forms drives your pay:\n- Your W-4 choices set how much federal tax is withheld.\n- Your state withholding choices set how much state tax is withheld.\n- Your direct deposit details send your pay to the right bank account.\n- Forms marked required must be finished before you can be assigned to production jobs.\n\n### How a Form Moves Along\n\nEach form follows the same path:\n1. **Set up** — An admin sets the form up.\n2. **Started** — You open the form and begin.\n3. **Saved** — You can save your progress and come back later.\n4. **Submitted** — Your answers are checked and submitted.\n5. **Signed** — Forms that need a signature are signed electronically, producing a legally valid copy.\n6. **Done** — The form is marked complete.\n\n### Filling Out Real Forms On Screen\n\nYou fill out the actual government forms on screen, not a simplified version. The layout matches the real paper W-4 or I-9 — the same sections, filing-status choices, amount lines, and signature blocks — so what you fill out is exactly what gets filed.\n\n### Signing\n\nForms that need a legally binding signature are signed electronically. The system takes your answers, fills in the official government form with them, and hands it to you to sign on screen. Your signed copy is stored securely and matches what you'd have filed on paper.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
