            Summary = "Complete reference for every field, button, status, validation rule, and action in the Compliance Forms module — including form list, submission statuses, form actions, submission history, identity documents, and validation rules.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 3,
            AppRoutes = """["/account/tax-forms"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"Compliance Forms Field Reference","groups":[{"heading":"Form List Fields","items":[{"label":"Form Icon","value":"A small picture next to each form that tells you which form it is. It turns into a green check once the form is finished."},{"label":"Form Name","value":"The official name of the form, shown as the card title (for example, 'W-4 Employee's Withholding Certificate' or 'I-9 Employment Eligibility Verification')."},{"label":"Description","value":"A short line under the name explaining what the form is for."},{"label":"Completion Date","value":"The date you finished and signed the form. It appears on the right side of a completed form."},{"label":"Required Badge","value":"A colored 'Required' label on forms you must finish before you can be assigned to production jobs."},{"label":"Onboarding Badge","value":"A colored 'Completed in onboarding' label on forms that are meant to be filled out through the guided onboarding steps rather than one at a time."},{"label":"Arrow Icon","value":"A small arrow on the right of each card. It just means the card is clickable and will open the form when you click it."}]},{"heading":"Form Submission Statuses","items":[{"label":"Pending","value":"You've started the form but haven't finished it yet. Any progress you saved is kept, and signing may still be in progress."},{"label":"Opened","value":"You've opened the signing step but haven't finished signing yet. This is a stage between started and done."},{"label":"Completed","value":"The form is fully filled out and signed, and your signed copy is ready to download. For the I-9, both your part and your employer's part are done."},{"label":"Expired","value":"The signing window ran out before you finished. Just start the form again to get a fresh signing link."},{"label":"Declined","value":"The signing was declined. Start the form again, or reach out to HR if you're not sure why."}]},{"heading":"Form Actions and Buttons","items":[{"label":"Onboarding Banner","value":"A banner at the top of the Tax Forms page linking to the guided onboarding steps. It appears only while you still have forms to finish."},{"label":"Back","value":"Returns you to the Tax Forms list from a form you've opened."},{"label":"Save Draft","value":"Saves what you've entered so far without submitting, so you can come back and finish later."},{"label":"Submit","value":"Checks that everything required is filled in, then submits the form. For forms that need a signature, this starts the signing step."},{"label":"Start E-Sign","value":"Begins the signing step for a form that hasn't been started yet."},{"label":"Download","value":"Downloads your signed copy of a completed form."},{"label":"Update","value":"Reopens a completed form so you can change your information. It isn't available on the I-9, which can't be changed once submitted."},{"label":"Acknowledge & Complete","value":"Marks simple sign-off forms as done, such as the workers' comp and handbook acknowledgments."},{"label":"Supporting Identity Documents","value":"Opens a window where you upload the ID documents needed for the I-9. A badge shows how many you've uploaded so far."},{"label":"Prev / Next","value":"Move between pages on a multi-page form. The page count (for example, '1 / 2') shows where you are."}]},{"heading":"Submission History","items":[{"label":"Completed Banner","value":"A green banner at the top of a finished form showing the date you completed it."},{"label":"In-Progress Banner","value":"A yellow banner shown when a form is started but not finished, along with the date you began it."},{"label":"W-4 Summary","value":"After you finish, shows your filing status, whether you have multiple jobs, and whether you claimed exempt. It doesn't show sensitive details like your Social Security number."},{"label":"I-9 Summary","value":"After you finish, shows your citizenship status and how many documents you provided, plus a reminder that the I-9 can't be changed once submitted."},{"label":"State Withholding Summary","value":"After you finish, shows your filing status, allowances, any extra withholding amount, and whether you claimed exempt."},{"label":"Direct Deposit Summary","value":"After you finish, shows your bank name and account type, with only the last four digits of your routing and account numbers shown for safety."},{"label":"Acknowledgment Summary","value":"For workers' comp and handbook forms, simply shows the date you acknowledged it."},{"label":"Signing Window","value":"The area where you sign your form on screen. It may ask for camera and microphone access to confirm your identity."},{"label":"Setup-in-Progress Banner","value":"A message telling you the form isn't ready to fill out yet and to contact your administrator. It goes away once setup is finished."}]},{"heading":"Identity Documents (I-9)","items":[{"label":"List A Documents","value":"Documents that prove both who you are and that you can work in the U.S., such as a U.S. Passport or Permanent Resident Card. One List A document is enough on its own."},{"label":"List B Documents","value":"Documents that prove who you are, such as a driver's license or state ID. These must be paired with a List C document."},{"label":"List C Documents","value":"Documents that prove you can work in the U.S., such as a Social Security card or birth certificate. These must be paired with a List B document."},{"label":"Upload a Document","value":"Drop a file into the upload area for each list. It accepts PDF, JPG, and PNG files up to 10 MB."},{"label":"Verification Status","value":"Each document shows either a green 'Verified' mark with a date or a 'Pending verification' note until a manager checks it against the original."},{"label":"Document Type","value":"The kind of document you uploaded, shown under the file name (for example, passport or driver's license)."},{"label":"Remove","value":"Deletes a document you uploaded. You'll be asked to confirm first."},{"label":"Done","value":"Closes the identity-documents window and returns you to the form."},{"label":"Document Requirement","value":"The I-9 needs either one List A document, or one List B plus one List C document. If something's missing, the Submit button tells you exactly what to add."}]},{"heading":"Validation Rules","items":[{"label":"Required Fields","value":"You must fill in every field marked required before you can submit. If you hover over a disabled Submit button, it tells you what's still missing."},{"label":"Social Security Number","value":"The Social Security number field adds the dashes for you as you type."},{"label":"Filing Status","value":"W-4 and state withholding forms need you to pick a filing status before you can submit."},{"label":"Signature","value":"To sign, type your full legal name. The date is filled in for you automatically."},{"label":"I-9 Documents","value":"Before submitting the I-9, you need either one List A document, or one List B plus one List C document. The Submit button tells you which list is still missing."},{"label":"Employer's I-9 Deadline","value":"Your employer must finish their part of the I-9 within three business days of your first day of work."},{"label":"Work Authorization Renewal","value":"If your work authorization has an expiration date, HR is reminded to renew the check before it lapses."},{"label":"Form Version","value":"Each form you submit is saved with the exact version you filled out, so your signed copy always matches what you saw, even if the form is updated later."},{"label":"Required-for-Jobs Forms","value":"Forms marked required must be finished before you can be assigned to production jobs. The system enforces this automatically."},{"label":"Resubmitting","value":"You can reopen and update most forms with the Update button. The I-9 is the exception; it can't be changed once submitted."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Knowledge Check (Quiz) ───────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Compliance Forms Knowledge Check",
            Slug = "compliance-forms-quiz",
            Summary = "Test your knowledge of the Compliance Forms module: form types, submission lifecycle, identity documents, validation rules, and payroll integration.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/account/tax-forms"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"cf1","text":"You're a new employee and need to complete your tax and work-eligibility forms. What's the easiest way to do this?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to your Tax Forms page and fill out each form one by one"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the guided onboarding steps, which walk you through all your required forms in one flow","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Ask your manager to fill the forms out for you"},{"id":"d","text":"Download the forms from the IRS website, fill them out on paper, and scan them"}],"explanation":"The guided onboarding steps walk new employees through all six forms (W-4, I-9, state withholding, direct deposit, workers' comp, and handbook) in one flow. Your Tax Forms page shows a banner linking to onboarding whenever forms are still unfinished."},{"id":"cf2","text":"You finished your W-4 during onboarding but just got married. What should you do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the W-4 can't be changed once you submit it"},{"id":"b","text":"Ask HR to delete your old W-4 so you can start over"},{"id":"c","text":"Open your W-4 on the Tax Forms page and click Update to resubmit it with your new filing status","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Mail a paper W-4 correction to the IRS yourself"}],"explanation":"You can update your W-4 any time your situation changes. Open your Tax Forms page, click your completed W-4, and click Update. That reopens the form so you can change your filing status and other choices."},{"id":"cf3","text":"You finished your I-9 during onboarding, then noticed a typo in your name. What can you do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Open the I-9 on your Tax Forms page and click Update to fix it"},{"id":"b","text":"Delete the I-9 and start over from onboarding"},{"id":"c","text":"Contact HR — the I-9 can't be changed once submitted","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Edit the signed PDF and re-upload it"}],"explanation":"The I-9 can't be changed once you submit it. There's no Update button on a finished I-9, and it shows a note reminding you to contact HR for any corrections."},{"id":"cf4","text":"What ID documents does the I-9 require?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A driver's license and a Social Security card"},{"id":"b","text":"Either one List A document (proves identity and work eligibility), OR one List B document (identity) plus one List C document (work eligibility)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Any two photo IDs"},{"id":"d","text":"A passport, with no other option accepted"}],"explanation":"The I-9 needs either one List A document, which proves both who you are and that you can work (like a U.S. Passport), or a List B document for identity (like a driver's license) plus a List C document for work eligibility (like a Social Security card)."},{"id":"cf5","text":"You uploaded a driver's license (List B) for your I-9, but the Submit button is still grayed out. Why?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The driver's license file type isn't accepted"},{"id":"b","text":"You also need a List C document for work eligibility — a List B document alone isn't enough","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A manager hasn't verified the document yet"},{"id":"d","text":"You need to upload at least three documents"}],"explanation":"A driver's license is a List B document, which only proves identity. You also need a List C document for work eligibility, such as a Social Security card or birth certificate. The Submit button will tell you a List C document is still missing."},{"id":"cf6","text":"What happens after you submit your W-4 in the on-screen form?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Your answers are emailed straight to the IRS"},{"id":"b","text":"The system fills in the official W-4 with your answers and sends it to you to sign electronically","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A manager has to approve it before it takes effect"},{"id":"d","text":"It's saved, but you have to print and sign a paper copy separately"}],"explanation":"For forms that need a signature, submitting fills the official government PDF with your answers and then hands it to you to sign electronically. Your signed copy is stored securely and you can download it any time."},{"id":"cf7","text":"A form on your Tax Forms page shows a 'Required' badge. What does that mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The form has an error you need to fix"},{"id":"b","text":"You have to finish it before you can be assigned to production jobs","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The form is past its yearly renewal date"},{"id":"d","text":"An admin flagged it for urgent attention"}],"explanation":"A 'Required' badge means the form must be finished before you can be assigned to production jobs. The system enforces this, so completing it clears the block."},{"id":"cf8","text":"You're filling out the state withholding form. How does the system know which state's form to show you?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You pick your state from a menu on the form"},{"id":"b","text":"It uses your home address from your profile"},{"id":"c","text":"It picks the right state form automatically from your assigned work location","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Everyone fills out the same generic state form"}],"explanation":"The system chooses your state withholding form from your assigned work location. It checks that location's state, sees whether the state has income tax, and shows you the right form for it."},{"id":"cf9","text":"You want to save your progress on a form and finish it later. What should you do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Take a screenshot and start over from scratch later"},{"id":"b","text":"Click Save Draft — your entries are kept so you can pick up where you left off","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"You can't save; the form has to be finished in one sitting"},{"id":"d","text":"Close the tab — it saves every keystroke automatically"}],"explanation":"Save Draft keeps what you've entered without submitting the form. When you come back, your saved entries load automatically so you can continue where you left off."},{"id":"cf10","text":"What's the difference between the 'Pending' and 'Opened' statuses?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Pending means you haven't started; Opened means you're filling it out"},{"id":"b","text":"Pending means you've started but haven't opened the signing step; Opened means you've opened the signing step","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Pending means waiting for a manager; Opened means the manager reviewed it"},{"id":"d","text":"There's no difference — they mean the same thing"}],"explanation":"Pending means you've started the form, and your progress may be saved, but you haven't opened the signing step yet. Opened means you've opened the signing step. Both come before the form is finished."},{"id":"cf11","text":"An employer (manager or admin) has to finish the employer part of an employee's I-9. What's the deadline?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Within 24 hours of the hire date"},{"id":"b","text":"Within three business days of the employee's first day of work","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Within 30 days of the start date"},{"id":"d","text":"There's no deadline"}],"explanation":"By law, the employer part of the I-9 must be finished within three business days of the employee's first day of work. The clock starts once the employee signs their part, which must come first."},{"id":"cf12","text":"You live in Texas and are asked to complete state withholding. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You fill out the standard Texas withholding form"},{"id":"b","text":"The system shows that Texas has no state income tax, so no form is needed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"You have to fill out the federal W-4 again instead"},{"id":"d","text":"An error appears because Texas isn't supported"}],"explanation":"Texas is one of several states with no state income tax, along with Florida and Nevada. When your work location is in one of these states, you're told no state withholding form is needed and you fill out nothing."},{"id":"cf13","text":"After you finish a W-4, what does the summary card show?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Your full Social Security number, exact withholding amounts, and the employer's tax ID"},{"id":"b","text":"Your filing status, whether you have multiple jobs, and whether you claimed exempt — no sensitive details","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Nothing — the summary is blank for security"},{"id":"d","text":"A link to download the raw form data"}],"explanation":"The W-4 summary shows only non-sensitive details: your filing status, whether you have multiple jobs, and whether you claimed exempt. Sensitive information like your Social Security number is never shown back to you."},{"id":"cf14","text":"Why does the system save the exact version of the form you filled out?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"So it can lock the form to a particular color theme"},{"id":"b","text":"So your signed copy always matches what you saw, even if the form is later updated to a newer version","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"So you can only submit the form once a year"},{"id":"d","text":"So the employer has to approve the version before you can use it"}],"explanation":"Each submission is tied to the exact form version you filled out. That way, if the government later releases a new version, your old signed copy still shows the layout you actually used. Only new submissions pick up the newer version."},{"id":"cf15","text":"How do you download a signed copy of a completed form?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Open the completed form on your Tax Forms page and click Download","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Ask HR to email you a copy"},{"id":"c","text":"Search the Files section for compliance documents"},{"id":"d","text":"You can't download signed copies — you can only view them on screen"}],"explanation":"On a completed form, click Download to save the signed copy. It downloads with the form's name as the file name, so it's easy to find later."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Admin: Form Templates (Article) ──────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Compliance Forms for Administrators",
            Slug = "compliance-admin-templates",
            Summary = "How administrators manage compliance form templates from Admin > Compliance: create/edit/delete custom templates, set the flags that control behavior (requires identity docs, blocks job assignment, auto-sync), extract an electronic form definition from a government PDF, and resolve the 'pending setup' state.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 7,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/compliance"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","admin","templates","configuration"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Compliance Forms for Administrators\n\nAdministrators configure which compliance forms an employee must complete, how each form behaves, and how the system renders it electronically. This all lives on the **Compliance** tab of the Admin area, which opens the form-templates panel. This tab is the default landing tab for Managers and Office Managers who don't have the broader Admin tabs.\n\n> Access: creating, editing, and deleting templates is **Admin-only**. If compliance forms are turned off for your company, the whole tab is hidden.\n\n### The Templates Panel\n\nThe panel header shows the template count plus two actions: **Sync All** (re-pulls the source PDF for every auto-sync template) and **New Template** (the green create button). Below that is a data table of every template with these columns:\n\n- **Icon** — the Material icon shown to employees on their Tax Forms list.\n- **Name** — the official form name. If a template still needs its fillable form built, a colored **Needs setup** label appears next to the name.\n- **Type** — the form type: W-4, I-9, State Withholding, Direct Deposit, Workers' Comp, or Handbook.\n- **Auto** / **Manual** label — whether the template updates itself from its source document or only when you refresh it by hand.\n- **Last Synced** — the last successful source pull, or *Never*.\n- **Active** / **Inactive** — whether employees see the form.\n- **Actions** — row-level icon buttons (see below).\n\n### System Templates vs Custom Templates\n\nThe six built-in form types (W-4, I-9, State Withholding, Direct Deposit, Workers' Comp, Handbook) ship as **system templates**. System templates can't be deleted, and their edit action opens an **upload-only** window — you can attach a document and set up how the PDF fills in, but you can't rename the form or change what it is. Custom templates you create yourself have a full edit dialog and can be deleted.\n\n### Creating a Custom Template\n\nClick **New Template** to open the create dialog. The fields are:\n\n- **Name** (required) — the form's display name.\n- **Form Type** (required) — one of the six types. This drives the summary card, identity-doc behavior, and resubmission rules.\n- **Description** — shown under the name on the employee's card.\n- **Icon** (required) — the small picture shown next to the form.\n- **Completion Key** (required) — ties this form to a step in the employee's onboarding progress and job-eligibility check. When they finish the form, that step is marked done.\n- **Source Document** — the web address of the official government PDF. Needed if you want the system to build the fillable form or keep it up to date automatically.\n- **Sort Order** — position in the employee's form list.\n- **Switches**: **Update automatically** (re-check the source document on a schedule), **Active** (visible to employees), **Requires Identity Docs** (turns on the List A / B / C upload window, used by the I-9), and **Required before jobs** (an unfinished form blocks the employee from production jobs and shows them a *Required* badge).\n\nClick **Create** to save. The validation button surfaces any missing required fields.\n\n### Editing a Template\n\nFor a custom template, the edit window has the same fields plus a **PDF field mapping**. The mapping matches each answer the employee gives to the right blank on the official government PDF. That's what lets the system pre-fill the real W-4 or I-9 before the employee signs it.\n\n### Extracting an Electronic Form Definition\n\nW-4, I-9, and State Withholding forms are filled out on screen — the employee fills the actual government layout, not a simplified version. The system builds that on-screen form from the official PDF:\n\n1. Set a **source document** (or upload one yourself) on the template.\n2. In the template's actions, click **Build the form** (the wand icon). It appears only when the template hasn't been built yet and has a source document.\n3. The system reads the PDF and builds a matching on-screen form — the same sections, filing-status choices, amount lines, signature blocks, and worksheets.\n4. When it finishes, the **Needs setup** label disappears and employees can fill out the form.\n\n### The 'Pending Setup' State\n\nUntil a form that should be built (W-4, I-9, State Withholding, or any template with a source document) has been built, it sits in a *needs setup* state. The template shows the **Needs setup** label, and any employee who opens that form sees a *not ready yet* message telling them to contact the administrator, instead of a fillable form. Fix it by building the form. Until then, employees can't complete it.\n\n### Configuring PDF Fill (system templates)\n\nFor system templates, the upload window also has a **PDF fill** section: attach a blank fillable PDF and provide the **field mapping**. Together these let the system fill the official PDF with the employee's answers before they sign it. A colored mark confirms the blank PDF is attached.\n\n### Syncing\n\n**Sync All** in the header re-checks the source document for every form set to update automatically. A **Refresh** button appears on individual forms that update automatically and have a source document, so you can refresh just one. The *Last Synced* column shows when each was last checked.\n\n### What Administrators Cannot Do\n\nAdmins set up templates and can handle the employer side of compliance (see *Managing Employee Compliance* and *Completing I-9 Section 2*). They do **not** fill in an employee's personal W-4 or I-9 details — employees complete their own forms through onboarding or their Tax Forms page. Admins also can't edit a submitted I-9 (federal law); corrections require a new submission.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Admin: State Withholding Configuration (Article) ─────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
