            AppRoutes = """["/admin/compliance"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","admin","state-withholding","tax"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## State Withholding Configuration\n\nState income-tax withholding is more complicated than a single form: every state handles it differently. Some have their own withholding certificate, some just use the federal W-4, and some have no income tax at all. QB Engineer's **State Withholding configuration dialog** gives administrators a single board to see and manage the readiness of all states.\n\n> Open this from the Compliance tab: on the form-templates list, the **State Withholding** row has an action button that opens the setup board.\n\n### How a State Form Gets Picked for an Employee\n\nThis is the key mental model. An employee never picks their state from a dropdown. Instead, the system picks the correct state withholding form from the employee's **assigned work location**. If an employee has no work location set, it falls back to the company's default location. That location's state decides which of the four groups below applies.\n\n### The Four State Buckets\n\nThe dialog opens with a summary strip of four counts, then lists every state grouped into four categories:\n\n1. **Ready to sign** — states that have their own withholding form and are already built. Employees in these states get a fully electronic fill-and-sign experience. Examples include states like California and New York once their forms are set up.\n\n2. **Needs a PDF** — states that have their own withholding form but **aren't built yet**. Employees in these states can't complete the form until an admin uploads the state's PDF and builds it. These cards are styled as pending. This bucket is your to-do list: it tells you exactly which state forms still need setup work.\n\n3. **Uses the federal W-4** — states that don't publish their own form and rely on the federal W-4 instead. Employees in these states don't fill a separate state form; their federal W-4 elections carry over.\n\n4. **No state income tax** — states with no income tax, such as Texas, Florida, Nevada, and Washington. Employees in these states see a message that no state withholding form is required, and complete nothing.\n\n### Reading and Selecting a State Card\n\nEach state card shows the **state code** (e.g., TX), the **state name**, the **form name** where applicable, and a **status chip** with an icon. The card for the employee's currently-resolved state is highlighted as active. Clicking a card selects that state — used when you're configuring or reviewing a specific state's setup. Cards are disabled while a save is in progress.\n\n### Typical Admin Workflow\n\n1. Open the dialog and look at the **Needs PDF upload** count. If it's zero, every state with its own form is ready.\n2. For each state in that group, get the official state withholding PDF, attach it to that state's template, and **build the form** (see *Compliance Forms for Administrators*).\n3. Once built, the state moves to **Ready to sign** and employees at locations in that state can complete the form on screen.\n4. States in the **Accept federal W-4** and **No state income tax** buckets need no action — they're informational and resolve automatically.\n\n### Why This Matters\n\nIf an employee's work location is in a state that's stuck in **Needs PDF upload**, that employee will hit a *pending setup* state on their state withholding form and can't finish onboarding's tax step. Keeping the Needs-a-PDF group empty for the states where you actually have employees is the practical goal — you don't need every U.S. state set up, only the ones your locations cover.","sections":[]}"""
