            Tags = """["compliance","admin","manager","i-9","identity-documents"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Managing Employee Compliance\n\nBeyond configuring templates, administrators, managers, and office managers handle the employer side of compliance: confirming employees have completed their forms, verifying the identity documents they uploaded, downloading signed PDFs for the file, and nudging people who are behind.\n\n> Access: the per-employee review actions (view detail, verify documents, send reminder, complete I-9 Section 2) are open to **Admin, Manager, and Office Manager** roles — not just full admins. The Users table on the Admin overview also shows a per-user compliance progress chip (e.g., 6/8) so you can spot who's incomplete at a glance.\n\n### Opening an Employee's Compliance Panel\n\nFrom Admin > Compliance, choose an employee. The per-employee compliance panel loads their full compliance picture. If no employee is selected, the panel shows a *select an employee* empty state.\n\nThe panel header shows the employee's name and email, and a **Send Reminder** button. Below the header, a **state withholding banner** summarizes how that employee's state is handled — no state tax, uses federal W-4, or a named state form — and shows the resolution source (their work location).\n\n### Form Submissions Table\n\nThe **Form Submissions** section lists every compliance form for the employee with:\n\n- **Form** — the template name.\n- **Status** — the submission status (Pending, Opened, Completed, Expired, Declined).\n- **I-9 sub-state chip** — for I-9 rows only, an extra chip shows the two-section state of the I-9 (Section 1 done by the employee, Section 2 done by the employer). This is how you tell at a glance whether you still owe Section 2.\n- **Signed** — the signed date, or an em dash if not signed.\n- **Actions** — a **Download** button (appears once a signed copy exists) to save it for your records, and — for an I-9 where the employee has signed their part but the employer part isn't done yet — a **Complete Section 2** action. See *Completing I-9 Section 2* for that flow.\n\n### Identity Documents Table\n\nThe **Identity Documents** section lists the List A / List B / List C documents the employee uploaded for their I-9, with:\n\n- **Type** — the document type/category.\n- **File** — the uploaded file name.\n- **Uploaded** — the upload date.\n- **Verified** — a green *Verified* chip once an admin/manager has confirmed it against the physical document, or a yellow *Pending* chip until then.\n- **Actions** — for documents not yet verified, a **Verify** button. Click it to mark a document verified after you've checked it against the original. This is a deliberate human step: the system stores and displays the upload, but a person must confirm it's genuine.\n\nIf the employee has no submissions or no identity documents yet, each section shows its own empty state.\n\n### Pay Stubs and Tax Documents\n\nThe same panel also surfaces the employee's **pay stubs** and **tax documents** (W-2 / 1099, etc.), each in its own table with download actions, and upload zones for adding manual records. Records sourced from a connected accounting provider show a *Synced* chip; manually-uploaded ones show *Manual* and can be deleted. (These overlap with the Payroll feature — covered there in depth.)\n\n### Sending a Compliance Reminder\n\nWhen an employee is behind on required forms, click **Send Reminder** in the panel header. This dispatches a notification prompting them to finish their outstanding compliance forms. Use it instead of chasing people manually — it's logged and routes through the normal notification system.\n\n### What You're Confirming\n\nThe employer-side job is verification and record-keeping, not data entry: confirm each required form reached **Completed**, confirm identity documents are **Verified**, complete **I-9 Section 2** within the deadline, and keep signed PDFs on file. You never edit the employee's personal entries on a W-4 or I-9 — those belong to the employee, and a submitted I-9 is immutable per federal law.","sections":[]}"""
