            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/compliance"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","i-9","section-2","admin","manager"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Completing I-9 Section 2\n\nThe I-9 is a two-part form by design. **Section 1** is the employee's attestation of identity and work authorization — they complete and sign it themselves. **Section 2** is the **employer's** responsibility: a company representative physically examines the employee's identity documents and records what they saw. QB Engineer routes Section 2 to Admins, Managers, and Office Managers.\n\n> The hard rule: **Section 2 must be completed within 3 business days of the employee's first day of work.** The deadline starts when the employee signs Section 1, and the system tracks it. Section 1 must be signed before Section 2 can begin.\n\n### Where to Start It\n\nOpen the employee's compliance panel (Admin > Compliance, then select the employee — see *Managing Employee Compliance*). In the **Form Submissions** table, an I-9 row that has Section 1 signed but Section 2 still outstanding shows a **Complete Section 2** action. Click it to open the Complete I-9 Section 2 window.\n\n### What the Dialog Asks For\n\n**Document List Type** (required) — choose how the employee proved identity and work authorization:\n\n- **List A** — a single document that establishes **both** identity and employment authorization (e.g., U.S. Passport, Permanent Resident Card, Employment Authorization Document). One List A document is sufficient.\n- **List B + C** — a **List B** document for identity (e.g., Driver's License, State ID) **plus** a **List C** document for employment authorization (e.g., Social Security Card, Birth Certificate). You need one of each.\n\n**First Day of Employment** (required) — the employee's start date, which anchors the 3-business-day deadline.\n\nDepending on your List Type choice, the dialog reveals document fields:\n\n- For **List A**: document type, document number, issuing authority, and expiration date — for the single List A document you inspected.\n- For **List B + C**: the same four fields for the **List B** document, then again for the **List C** document.\n\nRecord exactly what's on the physical document you examined. You're certifying that the documents appear genuine and relate to the employee.\n\n### Reverification\n\nAt the bottom, the **Work Authorization Expiration** date field captures when the employee's work authorization expires, if applicable. When set, the system schedules a **re-check** reminder so HR is prompted before the authorization lapses. Leave it blank for documents that don't expire (for example, a U.S. Passport for a citizen).\n\n### Saving\n\nClick **Complete Section 2**. If anything required is missing, the button tells you. On save, the employer section is recorded and the *Complete Section 2* action disappears from the row — the I-9 now reads as fully done.\n\n### What You Cannot Do Afterward\n\nLike the rest of the I-9, a completed Section 2 is part of an immutable federal record. The employee can't edit their submitted I-9, and corrections to a completed I-9 follow USCIS correction rules rather than an in-app edit. If you realize you recorded the wrong document, follow your organization's I-9 correction procedure — don't try to delete and re-create the record.\n\n### Why the 3-Day Deadline Is Strict\n\nThe 3-business-day window is a federal requirement, not a soft target. Missing it is an I-9 compliance violation. The overdue tracking exists so the deadline is visible and actionable — make completing Section 2 part of every new hire's first week, right alongside getting them their equipment.","sections":[]}"""
