        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Compliance Forms — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "compliance-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case reference for Compliance Forms: AcroForm field-map + blank PDF setup, auto-sync from source URL, form-definition version pinning, I-9 reverification, sensitive-form masking, DocuSeal recovery, and system vs custom templates.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/compliance"]""",
            Tags = """["compliance","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Compliance Forms — Advanced Reference\n\nEdge-case and background detail for the Compliance Forms area, available only when compliance forms are turned on for your company. The core modules cover the everyday flow; this is the side reading for the parts that only matter when you're setting up PDF fill, sorting out a stuck form, or handling the I-9 corner cases.\n\n## PDF Field Mapping + Blank PDF Setup\n\nA fill-and-sign form pre-fills the real government PDF before the employee signs it. Two things make that work:\n\n- **The blank PDF** — the empty official government PDF to be filled. You attach it in the upload window's PDF-fill section, and a colored mark confirms it's attached.\n- **The field mapping** — the connection between each answer the employee gives and the matching blank on that PDF.\n\nWhen the employee submits, the system fills the blank PDF using the mapping, keeps that filled-but-unsigned copy, and then hands it over for signing. If the mapping is missing or wrong, the wrong blank gets filled (or none does), and the signed copy won't match the answers. Both the blank PDF and the mapping are needed for true PDF fill. A form that's been built but has no mapping or blank PDF still collects answers and gets signed — it just won't reproduce the official paper layout.\n\n## Keeping Forms Up to Date\n\nThe source document is the web address of the official government PDF. When a form is set to update automatically, the system re-checks that address on a schedule and on demand. It only rebuilds the form when the document has actually changed, so re-checking an unchanged document costs nothing. The Last Synced date shows the most recent successful check (it reads *Never* until the first one).\n\n- **Sync All** (header button) re-checks every form set to update automatically.\n- **Refresh** (per-form button) re-checks a single form. It appears only on forms that update automatically and have a source document.\n\nWhen a check finds a new version, it creates a new form version (see below) rather than changing older ones. Forms set to manual never update on their own — they only change when an admin rebuilds them.\n\n## Form Versions\n\nEach time a form is built, it's saved as a new version (with the template, any state, the source document, an effective date, and the full layout). Every submission is tied to the exact version it was filled against. That's what lets a form be reproduced with its original layout years later, even after the government revises it and a newer version is built. In practice, re-checking a source never rewrites history — old submissions stay tied to their original version, and only new submissions pick up the newest one. State withholding versions also carry the state, so each submission keeps the right state layout.\n\n## I-9 Re-Check\n\nWhen the employer records Section 2 documents whose work authorization has an expiration date, that date is saved on the submission. It stays empty for documents that don't expire (a U.S. citizen, or a permanent resident with a non-expiring document). When set, it drives a re-check reminder so HR is prompted before the authorization lapses — a re-check is a fresh employer sign-off, separate from the original Section 2. Don't confuse it with the three-business-day deadline to *first* complete Section 2, which starts when Section 1 is signed; the re-check is about work authorization that expires later in employment.\n\n## Protecting Sensitive Details\n\nW-4, I-9, and State Withholding are sensitive forms. Their truly sensitive details — Social Security numbers, bank routing and account numbers, and I-9 document numbers — are stored encrypted and **never shown back**. A saved draft returns your ordinary answers plus a simple yes/no flag for whether each sensitive value is on file, rather than the value itself, and you're not forced to re-enter something you've already saved. When you resubmit a sensitive form, your earlier entries are **not** pre-filled — the form starts clean so an old stored value never resurfaces. Summaries show only non-sensitive details (filing status, yes/no flags) and the last four digits for direct deposit.\n\n## When Signing Doesn't Finish\n\nSigning can end without completing. A form moves from started, to opened for signing, to finished — plus two recovery outcomes: **Expired** (the signing link ran out before signing) and **Declined** (the signer declined). Recovery only goes forward: there's no resuming a dead link. The employee simply starts a **new** submission, which creates a fresh signing link and ties to the current form version. The signing result comes back automatically and is what marks the form opened, finished, or declined and stores the signed copy. The signing window shows only while a live signing link exists and the form is started or opened; once it's expired or declined, the window is gone and Start E-Sign creates the replacement.\n\n## Built-in vs Custom Forms\n\nThe six built-in forms (W-4, I-9, State Withholding, Direct Deposit, Workers' Comp, Handbook) come with the system: they can't be deleted, and editing one only lets you attach a document and set up PDF fill — you can't rename it or change what it is. **Custom forms** you create have a full edit window (including the field mapping) and can be deleted. Both kinds can be built, updated automatically, carry the same switches (Active, Requires Identity Docs, Required before jobs), and tie to a completion step. The difference is what they are and how they're managed, not what they can do: built-in forms are the fixed set every company needs, and custom forms are the extra ones a particular shop adds.","sections":[]}"""
        });

